        <h2>2. Houzz Pro — Best for small residential contractors</h2>
        <p><strong>Pricing:</strong> Starter $99/mo · Essential $149/mo · Pro $199/mo</p>

        <p>For smaller residential contractors — remodelers, design-build firms, specialty interior contractors — Houzz Pro fills a niche Procore doesn't touch: combining project management with lead generation from the Houzz marketplace. If Procore's pricing is multiple times your monthly software budget, Houzz Pro at $99–$199/month is a legitimate alternative for smaller operations.</p>

        <p><strong>The unique advantage:</strong> Houzz's marketplace drives real homeowner leads to your profile, which Procore (or almost any other construction platform) doesn't attempt. For small contractors who spend money on marketing, this built-in lead generation has tangible ROI.</p>

        <div class="cta-box">
          <p><strong>Houzz Pro</strong> — CRM, project management, and lead generation in one tool for residential contractors.</p>
          <a href="https://www.houzz.com/pro" rel="nofollow sponsored" target="_blank" class="btn">Try Houzz Pro →</a>
        </div>

        <h2>3. Autodesk Build — Best Procore alternative for large commercial GCs</h2>
        <p><strong>Pricing:</strong> Custom (similar to Procore's enterprise range)</p>

        <p>Autodesk Build (part of Autodesk Construction Cloud) is the most credible Procore competitor in the enterprise commercial space. For large GCs already deeply integrated with Autodesk products — BIM 360, Revit, AutoCAD — Autodesk Build provides the strongest BIM-to-field workflow integration available. If your projects rely heavily on Revit models and you want tight connectivity between the design model and field management, Autodesk Build's integration advantage over Procore is real.</p>

        <p><strong>Key differences from Procore:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Superior BIM integration — Revit models, design data, and clash detection flow directly into field management</li>
          <li>Autodesk Docs as the backbone — one document management system across design and construction</li>
          <li>Better for owners and architects who also use Autodesk tools and want to collaborate on one platform</li>
          <li>More flexible module-by-module adoption — you don't have to go all-in at once</li>
        </ul>

        <p><strong>Where Procore still wins:</strong> Procore's financial management, subcontractor network, and customer support have historically been stronger. The Procore platform also has a larger ecosystem of integrations and third-party apps.</p>

        <h2>4. Fieldwire — Best for field teams who don't need full PM</h2>
        <p><strong>Pricing:</strong> Free · Basic $29/user/mo · Pro $39/user/mo · Business $54/user/mo</p>

        <p>If your primary need is giving field teams — supers, foremen, trade subs — a fast, simple platform for plan access, task tracking, and punch lists, Fieldwire is dramatically simpler and cheaper than Procore. You don't get financials, contracts, or advanced reporting. But for field coordination, Fieldwire is faster to deploy and often more actually used by field crews than Procore's more complex interface.</p>

        <p><strong>The case for Fieldwire over Procore:</strong> A platform that field crews actually use beats a more powerful platform they ignore. Fieldwire's adoption rate in the field tends to be higher than Procore's for trade contractors and subcontractors who don't want to navigate a complex system. The free tier is also genuinely functional for small teams.</p>

        <h2>5. Knowify — Best Procore alternative for subcontractors</h2>
        <p><strong>Pricing:</strong> ~$149/mo starter</p>

        <p>Procore is designed primarily from the GC's perspective. Subcontractors using Procore often get access to a GC's project for collaboration but pay for their own separate platform to manage their business. Knowify is built entirely around how subcontractors operate — AIA billing, subcontract management, job costing against bid, and change order tracking. For commercial subs, it's a better-fit alternative to Procore at a lower price point.</p>

        <h2>6. JobTread — Best for small GCs watching the budget</h2>
        <p><strong>Pricing:</strong> Basic $99/mo · Pro $199/mo</p>

        <p>For small general contractors doing $500K–$5M in revenue who need job cost tracking, budgeting, and client communication — but don't need Procore's complexity — JobTread provides the core PM workflow at an accessible price. The budgeting and job cost tracking is notably strong relative to the price point.</p>

        <div class="cta-box">
          <p><strong>JobTread</strong> — Serious job costing for small GCs without enterprise pricing.</p>
          <a href="https://www.jobtread.com" rel="nofollow sponsored" target="_blank" class="btn">Try JobTread →</a>
        </div>

        <h2>When Procore is actually the right choice</h2>
        <p>Despite this roundup, Procore is genuinely the right answer for some contractors. Consider Procore if:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>You're a commercial GC doing $20M+ in revenue with complex financial management needs</li>
          <li>Your GC clients require you to be on Procore — this is increasingly common in commercial construction</li>
          <li>You need the deepest integration ecosystem (300+ app marketplace)</li>
          <li>Bid management, subcontractor prequalification, and owner portals are critical features</li>
          <li>You have an IT team that can manage implementation and ongoing administration</li>
        </ul>

        <p>If you don't meet these criteria, one of the alternatives above likely fits better and will cost significantly less.</p>

